<section xml:id="section-combining-like-terms">

    <title>Combining Like Terms</title>
    <objectives>
        <title>PCC Course Content and Outcome Guide</title>
        <ul>
            <li><xref ref="mth60-simplify-algebraic-expressions" /></li>
        </ul>
    </objectives>


    <introduction>
        <p>In the last section we worked with algebraic expressions. In order to simplify algebraic expressions, it is useful to identify which quantities we can combine.</p>

        <figure>
            <caption>Alternative Video Lesson</caption>
            <video youtubelist="" />
        </figure>
    </introduction>

    <subsection>
        <title>Identifying Terms</title>
        <p>In an algebraic expression, the <term>terms</term><idx><h>term</h></idx> are the quantities that are added. For example, the expression <m>3x+2y</m> has two terms, which are <m>3x</m> and <m>2y</m>. Let's look at some more examples.</p>

        <example>
            <p>List the terms in the expression <m>2l+2w</m>.</p>
            <p>The expression has two terms that are being added, <m>2l</m> and <m>2w</m>.</p>
        </example>

        <p>If there is any subtraction, we will rewrite the expression using addition. Here is an example of that.</p>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>List the terms in the expression <m>-2x+5x-4</m>.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>We can rewrite this expression as <m>-2x+5x+(-4)</m> to see that the terms are <m>-2x</m>, <m>5x</m>, and <m>-4</m>. The last term is negative because subtracting is the same as adding the opposite.</p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>List the terms in the expression <m>3cm+2cm+3cm+2cm</m>.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>This expression has four terms: <m>3cm</m>, <m>2cm</m>, <m>3cm</m>, and <m>2cm</m>.</p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <p>Now you can try this one.</p>

        <example>
            <!-- TODO: Make this example a checkpoint -->
            <statement>
                <p>List the terms in the expression <m>5x-4y+10z</m>.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>The terms are <m>5x</m>, <m>-4y</m>, and <m>10z</m>.</p>
            </solution>
        </example>

    </subsection>

 <subsection>
        <title>Combining Like Terms</title>
        <p>In the examples above, you may have wanted to combine some of the terms. Look at the quantities below to see which ones you can add or subtract.</p>

            <sidebyside margins="0%">
            <tabular halign="center">
                <row>
                    <cell><m>5</m> inches <m>+ 20</m> inches</cell>
                    <cell><m>16</m> ft <m>- 4</m> ft<m>^2</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>2\apple+5\apple</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>5</m> minutes <m>+ 50</m> feet</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>5\dog-2\cat</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>20</m> meters<m>- 6</m> meters</cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
        </sidebyside>

        <p>The terms that we can combine are called <term>like terms</term><idx><h>like term</h></idx>. We can combine terms with the same units, but we cannot combine units such as minutes and feet or cats and dogs. Here are the answers:</p>

        <sidebyside margins="0%">
            <tabular halign="center">
                <row>
                    <cell><m>5</m> inches <m>+ 20</m> inches<m>=25</m> inches</cell>
                    <cell><m>16</m> ft <m>- 4</m> ft<m>^2</m> cannot be simplified</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>2\apple+5\apple=7\apple</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>5</m> minutes <m>+ 50</m> feet cannot be simplified</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>5\dog-2\cat</m> cannot be simplified</cell>
                    <cell><m>20</m> meters<m>- 6</m> meters <m>=14</m> meters</cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
        </sidebyside>

        <p>Note that we could combine units such as feet and inches if we convert one of the terms first. Now let's look at some examples that have variables in them. Which ones can you combine?</p>

        <sidebyside margins="0%">
            <tabular halign="center">
                <row>
                    <cell><m>10x+3y</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>4x-8x</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>9y-4y</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>-6x+17z</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>-3x-7x</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>5t+8t^2</m></cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
        </sidebyside>

        <p>The terms that we can combine have the same variable part, including any exponents. Here are the answers:</p>

        <sidebyside margins="0%">
            <tabular halign="center">
                <row>
                    <cell><m>10x+3y</m> cannot be simplifed</cell>
                    <cell><m>4x-8x=-4x</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>9y-4y=5y</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>-6x+17z</m> cannot be simplified</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>-3x-7x=-10x</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>5t+8t^2</m> cannot be simplifed</cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
        </sidebyside>

        <example>
            <p>Simplify the expression <m>20x-16x+4y</m>, if possible, by combining like terms.</p>
            <p>This expression has two like terms, <m>20x</m> and <m>-16x</m>, which we can combine. <md>
            <mrow>20x-16x+4y</mrow>
            <mrow>=4x+4y</mrow></md>
            Note we cannot combine <m>4x</m> and <m>4y</m> because <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> represent different quantities.</p>
        </example>

        <example>
            <p>Simplify the expression <m>100x+100x^2</m>, if possible, by combining like terms.</p>
            <p>This expression cannot be simplified because the variable parts are not the same. We cannot add <m>x</m> and <m>x^2</m> just like we cannot add feet, a measure of length, and square feet, a measure of area.</p>
        </example>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>Simplify the expression <m>-10r+2s-5t</m>, if possible, by combining like terms.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>This expression cannot be simpified because there aren't any like terms.</p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>Simplify the expression <m>x+5x</m>, if possible, by combining like terms.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>This expression can be thought of as <m>1x+5x</m>. When we have a single <m>x</m>, the <m>1</m> is not usually written. Now we have two like terms, <m>1x</m> and <m>5x</m>. We will add those together to get <m>6x</m>.</p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <p>So far we have combined terms with whole numbers but we can also combine parts of things.</p>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>Simplify the expression <m>x-0.15x</m>, if possible, by combining like terms.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>This expression can be rewritten as <m>1.00x-0.15x</m>. Then we can see how to combine them and we get <m>0.85x</m>.</p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <p>Now you can try these.</p>

        <example>
            <!-- TODO: Make this one a checkpoint -->
            <statement>
                <p>Simplify each expression, if possible, by combining like terms.<ol label="a.">
                    <li>
                        <p><m>4x-7y+10x</m></p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p><m>y-8y+2x^2</m></p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p><m>x+0.25x</m></p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p><m>4x+1.5y-9z</m></p>
                    </li>
                </ol></p>

            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p><ol label="a.">
                    <li>
                        <p>This expression has two like terms that can be combined to get <m>14x-7y</m>.</p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>In this expression we can combine the <m>y</m> terms to get <m>-7y+2x^2</m>.</p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>Rewrite this expression as <m>1.00x+0.25x</m> and simplify to get <m>1.25x</m>.</p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>This expression cannot be simplified further because there aren't any like terms.</p>
                    </li>
                </ol></p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <aside>
            <title>The Difference Between Terms and Factors</title>

            <p>We have learned that terms are quantities that are added, such as <m>3x</m> and <m>-2x</m> in <m>3x-2x</m>. These are different than <term>factors</term><idx><h>factor</h></idx>, which are parts that are multiplied together. For example, the term <m>2x</m> has two factors: <m>2</m> and <m>x</m> (with the multiplication symbol implied between them). The term <m>2\pi r</m> has three factors: <m>2</m>, <m>\pi</m>, and <m>r</m>.</p>
        </aside>

    </subsection>

<!-- Note: I outlined one of each type of exercise. -->
    <exercises>
        <exercisegroup cols="2">
            <exercise>
                <statement>
                    <p>Count the number of terms in the expression.<ol label="a." cols="2">
                        <li><p><m>5x+10y-3z</m></p></li>
                        <li><p><m>-2t+s</m></p></li>
                        <li><p><m>2x</m></p></li>
                        <li><p><m>9x-2z-4x+z</m></p></li>
                    </ol></p>
                </statement>
                <solution>
                    <p><ol label="a." cols="2">
                        <li><p>This expression has <m>3</m> terms.</p></li>
                        <li><p>This expression has <m>2</m> terms.</p></li>
                        <li><p>This expression has <m>1</m> term.</p></li>
                        <li><p>This expression has <m>4</m> terms.</p></li>
                    </ol></p>
                </solution>
            </exercise>
        </exercisegroup>

        <exercisegroup cols="2">
            <exercise>
                <statement>
                    <p>List the terms in the expression.<ol label="a." cols="2">
                        <li><p><m>-2x+4y</m>.</p></li>
                        <li><p><m>8x^2-20x^2+4x</m></p></li>
                        <li><p><m>5a-2b+6a-7b</m></p></li>
                        <li><p><m>x</m></p></li>
                    </ol></p>
                </statement>
                <solution>
                    <p><ol label="a." cols="2">
                        <li><p>The terms are <m>-2x</m> and <m>4y</m>.</p></li>
                        <li><p>The terms are <m>8x^2</m>, <m>-20x^2</m>, and <m>4x</m>.</p></li>
                        <li><p>The terms are <m>5a</m>, <m>-2b</m>, <m>6a</m>, and <m>-7b</m>.</p></li>
                        <li><p>The term is <m>x</m>.</p></li>
                    </ol></p>
                </solution>
            </exercise>
        </exercisegroup>

        <exercisegroup cols="2">
            <exercise>
                <statement>
                    <p>Where possible, simplify the following expressions by combining like terms.<ol label="a." cols="2">
                        <li><p><m>6c+12c-5c</m></p></li>
                        <li><p><m>-5q^2-3q^2</m></p></li>
                        <li><p><m>-3x-5y+4.5x</m></p></li>
                        <li><p><m>2x-3y+4z</m></p></li>
                    </ol></p>
                </statement>
                <solution>
                    <p><ol label="a.">
                        <li><p>All three terms are like terms, so they may combined. We combine them two at a time:<md>
                            <mrow>6c+12c-5c \amp=18c-5c</mrow>
                            <mrow>\amp=13c</mrow>
                        </md></p></li>
                        <li><p>The two terms <m>-5q^2</m> and <m>-3q^2</m> are like terms, so we may combine them:<md>
                            <mrow>-5q^2-3q^2 \amp=-8q^2</mrow>
                        </md></p></li>
                        <li><p>The two terms <m>-3x</m> and <m>4.5x</m> are like terms so we can combine them, while the other term is different.<md>
                            <mrow>-3x-5y+4.5x</mrow>
                            <mrow>\amp=1.5x-5y</mrow>
                        </md></p></li>
                        <li><p>The expression <m>2x-3y+4z</m> cannot be simplified as there are no like terms.</p></li>
                    </ol></p>
                </solution>
            </exercise>
        </exercisegroup>

    </exercises>

</section>

